\title{Condition: Stateful trigger and analysis unit}
\description{
A \code{Condition} encapsulates a single trigger rule that is evaluated against
a data snapshot at each simulated timepoint. It combines three concerns:

\enumerate{
\item \strong{Filtering} — a \code{dplyr::filter()} expression selects the rows
relevant to this condition (e.g. "only enrolled subjects in arm A").
\item \strong{Analysis} — an optional function transforms the filtered snapshot
into a result (e.g. a t-test, a subject count, a Go/No-Go decision).
\item \strong{Trigger bookkeeping} — the condition fires only when the
filtered data is non-empty, the cooldown period has elapsed since the
last trigger, and the maximum trigger count has not been reached.
}

\code{Condition} objects are stored in \code{trial$conditions} and evaluated by
\code{\link{Trial}}\verb{$run()} at each timepoint.
}
\details{
\strong{Three-gate logic.} A trigger fires only when all three gates pass:
\enumerate{
\item The filtered snapshot contains at least one row.
\item \code{current_time - last_trigger_time >= cooldown} (or the condition
has never fired before).
\item \code{trigger_count < max_triggers}.
}
If any gate fails, \code{check_conditions()} returns an empty list and state
is not updated.

On a successful trigger, the condition calls
\code{analysis(filtered_data, current_time)} and stores the result under
\code{name} (or \code{1L} when no name is set). If no analysis function is
provided, the filtered data frame is returned as-is with a warning.
}
